# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: web-audio-api
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] The **`AudioNode`** interface is a generic interface for representing an audio processing module.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] Returns the associated `BaseAudioContext`, that is the object representing the processing graph the node is participating in.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] Returns the number of inputs feeding the node.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] Source nodes are defined as nodes having a `numberOfInputs` property with a value of `0`.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] Returns the number of outputs coming out of the node.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] Destination nodes — like `AudioDestinationNode` — have a value of `0` for this attribute.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] Represents an integer used to determine how many channels are used when up-mixing and down-mixing connections to any inputs to the node.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] Its usage and precise definition depend on the value of `AudioNode.channelCountMode`.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] Represents an enumerated value describing the way channels must be matched between the node's inputs and outputs.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] Represents an enumerated value describing the meaning of the channels.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] This interpretation will define how audio up-mixing and down-mixing will happen.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] The possible values are `"speakers"` or `"discrete"`.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] Allows us to connect the output of this node to be input into another node, either as audio data or as the value of an `AudioParam`.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] Allows us to disconnect the current node from another one it is already connected to.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] Each `AudioNode` has inputs and outputs, and multiple audio nodes are connected to build a *processing graph*.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] This graph is contained in an `AudioContext`, and each audio node can only belong to one audio context.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] A *source node* has zero inputs but one or multiple outputs, and can be used to generate sound.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] On the other hand, a *destination node* has no outputs; instead, all its inputs are directly played back on the speakers (or whatever audio output device the audio context uses).
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] In addition, there are *processing nodes* which have inputs and outputs.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] The more nodes in a graph, the higher the latency will be.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] For example, if your graph has a latency of 500ms, when the source node plays a sound, it will take half a second until that sound can be heard on your speakers (or even longer because of latency in the underlying audio device).
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] Therefore, if you need to have interactive audio, keep the graph as small as possible, and put user-controlled audio nodes at the end of a graph.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] For example, a volume control (`GainNode`) should be the last node so that volume changes take immediate effect.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] Each input and output has a given amount of *channels*.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] For example, mono audio has one channel, while stereo audio has two channels.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] The Web Audio API will up-mix or down-mix the number of channels as required; check the Web Audio spec for details.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] For a list of all audio nodes, see the Web Audio API homepage.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] There are two ways to create an `AudioNode`: via the *constructor* and via the *factory method*.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] This simple snippet of code shows the creation of some audio nodes, and how the `AudioNode` properties and methods can be used.
[src:web-audio-api/api-audionode] You can find examples of such usage on any of the examples linked to on the Web Audio API landing page (for example Violent Theremin).
[src:web-audio-api/api-gainnode] The `GainNode` interface represents a change in volume.
[src:web-audio-api/api-gainnode] It is an `AudioNode` audio-processing module that causes a given gain to be applied to the input data before its propagation to the output.
[src:web-audio-api/api-gainnode] A `GainNode` always has exactly one input and one output, both with the same number of channels.
[src:web-audio-api/api-gainnode] The gain is a unitless value, changing with time, that is multiplied to each corresponding sample of all input channels.
[src:web-audio-api/api-gainnode] If modified, the new gain is instantly applied, causing unaesthetic 'clicks' in the resulting audio.
[src:web-audio-api/api-gainnode] To prevent this from happening, never change the value directly but use the exponential interpolation methods on the `AudioParam` interface.
[src:web-audio-api/api-gainnode] Creates and returns a new `GainNode` object.
[src:web-audio-api/api-gainnode] As an alternative, you can use the `BaseAudioContext.createGain()` factory method; see Creating an AudioNode.
[src:web-audio-api/api-gainnode] An a-rate `AudioParam` representing the amount of gain to apply.
[src:web-audio-api/api-gainnode] You have to set `AudioParam.value` or use the methods of `AudioParam` to change the effect of gain.
[src:web-audio-api/api-gainnode] See `BaseAudioContext.createGain()` for example code showing how to use an `AudioContext` to create a `GainNode`.
[src:web-audio-api/audiocontext] It’s been available across browsers since April 2021.
[src:web-audio-api/audiocontext] The `AudioContext` interface represents an audio-processing graph built from audio modules linked together, each represented by an `AudioNode`.
[src:web-audio-api/audiocontext] An audio context controls both the creation of the nodes it contains and the execution of the audio processing, or decoding.
[src:web-audio-api/audiocontext] You need to create an `AudioContext` before you do anything else, as everything happens inside a context.
[src:web-audio-api/audiocontext] It's recommended to create one AudioContext and reuse it instead of initializing a new one each time, and it's OK to use a single `AudioContext` for several different audio sources and pipeline concurrently.
[src:web-audio-api/audiocontext] Creates and returns a new `AudioContext` object.
[src:web-audio-api/audiocontext] Returns the number of seconds of processing latency incurred by the `AudioContext` passing the audio from the `AudioDestinationNode` to the audio subsystem.
[src:web-audio-api/audiocontext] Returns an estimation of the output latency of the current audio context.
[src:web-audio-api/audiocontext] Returns an `AudioPlaybackStats` object providing access to duration, underrun, and latency statistics for the `AudioContext`.
[src:web-audio-api/audiocontext] Returns the sink ID of the current output audio device.
[src:web-audio-api/audiocontext] Closes the audio context, releasing any system audio resources that it uses.
[src:web-audio-api/audiocontext] Creates a `MediaElementAudioSourceNode` associated with an `HTMLMediaElement`.
[src:web-audio-api/audiocontext] This can be used to play and manipulate audio from `<video>` or `<audio>` elements.
[src:web-audio-api/audiocontext] Creates a `MediaStreamAudioSourceNode` associated with a `MediaStream` representing an audio stream which may come from the local computer microphone or other sources.
[src:web-audio-api/audiocontext] Creates a `MediaStreamAudioDestinationNode` associated with a `MediaStream` representing an audio stream which may be stored in a local file or sent to another computer.
[src:web-audio-api/audiocontext] Creates a `MediaStreamTrackAudioSourceNode` associated with a `MediaStream` representing a media stream track.
[src:web-audio-api/audiocontext] Returns a new `AudioTimestamp` object containing two audio timestamp values relating to the current audio context.
[src:web-audio-api/audiocontext] Resumes the progression of time in an audio context that has previously been suspended/paused.
[src:web-audio-api/audiocontext] Sets the output audio device for the `AudioContext`.
[src:web-audio-api/audiocontext] Suspends the progression of time in the audio context, temporarily halting audio hardware access and reducing CPU/battery usage in the process.
[src:web-audio-api/audiocontext] Fired when the output audio device (and therefore, the `AudioContext.sinkId`) has changed.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] In a digital audio system, an analog electrical signal representing the sound is converted with an analog-to-digital converter (ADC) into a digital signal, typically using pulse-code modulation (PCM).
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] This digital signal can then be recorded, edited, modified, and copied using computers, audio playback machines, and other digital tools.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] For playback, a digital-to-analog converter (DAC) performs the reverse process, converting a digital signal back into an analog signal, which is then sent through an audio power amplifier and ultimately to a loudspeaker.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Digital audio systems may include compression, storage, processing, and transmission components.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Conversion to a digital format allows convenient manipulation, storage, transmission, and retrieval of an audio signal.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Unlike analog audio, in which making copies of a recording results in generation loss and degradation of signal quality, digital audio allows an infinite number of copies to be made without any degradation of signal quality.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Digital audio technologies are used in the recording, manipulation, mass-production, and distribution of sound, including recordings of songs, instrumental pieces, podcasts, sound effects, and other sounds.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Modern online music distribution depends on digital recording and data compression.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] The availability of music as data files, rather than as physical objects, has significantly reduced the costs of distribution as well as making it easier to share copies.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Before digital audio, the music industry distributed and sold music by selling physical copies in the form of records and cassette tapes.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] With digital audio and online distribution systems such as iTunes, companies sell digital sound files to consumers, which the consumer receives over the Internet.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Popular streaming services such as Apple Music, Spotify, or YouTube, offer temporary access to the digital file, and are now the most common form of music consumption.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] An analog audio system converts physical waveforms of sound into electrical representations of those waveforms by use of a transducer, such as a microphone.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] The sounds are then stored on an analog medium such as magnetic tape, or transmitted through an analog medium such as a telephone line or radio.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] The process is reversed for reproduction: the electrical audio signal is amplified and then converted back into physical waveforms via a loudspeaker.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Analog audio retains its fundamental wave-like characteristics throughout its storage, transformation, duplication, and amplification.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Analog audio signals are susceptible to noise and distortion, due to the innate characteristics of electronic circuits and associated devices.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Disturbances in a digital system do not result in error unless they are so large as to result in a symbol being misinterpreted as another symbol or disturbing the sequence of symbols.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] It is, therefore, generally possible to have an entirely error-free digital audio system in which no noise or distortion is introduced between conversion to digital format and conversion back to analog.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] A digital audio signal may be encoded for correction of any errors that might occur in the storage or transmission of the signal.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] This technique, known as channel coding, is essential for broadcast or recorded digital systems to maintain bit accuracy.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Eight-to-fourteen modulation is the channel code used for the audio compact disc (CD).
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] If an audio signal is analog, a digital audio system starts with an ADC that converts an analog signal to a digital signal.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] The ADC runs at a specified sampling rate and converts at a known bit resolution.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] CD audio, for example, has a sampling rate of 44.1 kHz (44,100 samples per second), and has 16-bit resolution for each stereo channel.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Analog signals that have not already been bandlimited must be passed through an anti-aliasing filter before conversion, to prevent the aliasing distortion that is caused by audio signals with frequencies higher than the Nyquist frequency (half the sampling rate).
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] A digital audio signal may be stored or transmitted.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Digital audio can be stored on a CD, a digital audio player, a hard drive, a USB flash drive, or any other digital data storage device.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] The digital signal may be altered through digital signal processing, where it may be filtered or have effects applied.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Sample-rate conversion, including upsampling and downsampling, may be used to change signals that have been encoded with a different sampling rate to a common sampling rate prior to processing.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Audio data compression techniques, such as MP3, Advanced Audio Coding (AAC), Opus, Ogg Vorbis, or FLAC, are commonly employed to reduce the file size.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Digital audio can be carried over digital audio interfaces such as AES3 or MADI.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Digital audio can be carried over a network using audio over Ethernet, audio over IP or other streaming media standards and systems.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] For playback, digital audio must be converted back to an analog signal with a DAC.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] According to the Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem, with some practical and theoretical restrictions, a band-limited version of the original analog signal can be accurately reconstructed from the digital signal.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] During conversion, audio data can be embedded with a digital watermark to prevent piracy and unauthorized use.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Watermarking is done using a direct-sequence spread-spectrum (DSSS) method.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] The audio information is then modulated by a pseudo-noise (PN) sequence, then shaped within the frequency domain and put back in the original signal.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] The strength of the embedding determines the strength of the watermark on the audio data.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Pulse-code modulation (PCM) was invented by British scientist Alec Reeves in 1937.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Chapin Cutler of Bell Labs filed the patent on differential pulse-code modulation (DPCM), a data compression algorithm.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Adaptive DPCM (ADPCM) was introduced by P.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Perceptual coding was first used for speech coding compression, with linear predictive coding (LPC).
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Initial concepts for LPC date back to the work of Fumitada Itakura (Nagoya University) and Shuzo Saito (Nippon Telegraph and Telephone) in 1966.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Schroeder at Bell Labs developed a form of LPC called adaptive predictive coding (APC), a perceptual coding algorithm that exploited the masking properties of the human ear, followed in the early 1980s with the code-excited linear prediction (CELP) algorithm.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Discrete cosine transform (DCT) coding, a lossy compression method first proposed by Nasir Ahmed in 1972, provided the basis for the modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT), which was developed by J.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] The MDCT is the basis for most audio coding standards, such as Dolby Digital (AC-3), MP3 (MPEG Layer III), AAC, Windows Media Audio (WMA), Opus and Vorbis (Ogg).
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] PCM was used in telecommunications applications long before its first use in commercial broadcast and recording.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Commercial digital recording was pioneered in Japan by NHK and Nippon Columbia and their Denon brand, in the 1960s.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] The first commercial digital recordings were released in 1971.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] The BBC also began to experiment with digital audio in the 1960s.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] By the early 1970s, it had developed a 2-channel recorder, and in 1972 it deployed a digital audio transmission system that linked its broadcast center to its remote transmitters.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] The first 16-bit PCM recording in the United States was made by Thomas Stockham at the Santa Fe Opera in 1976, on a Soundstream recorder.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] An improved version of the Soundstream system was used to produce several classical recordings by Telarc in 1978.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] The 3M digital multitrack recorder in development at the time was based on BBC technology.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] The first all-digital album recorded on this machine was Ry Cooder's *Bop till You Drop* in 1979.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] British record label Decca began development of its own 2-track digital audio recorders in 1978 and released the first European digital recording in 1979.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Popular professional digital multitrack recorders produced by Sony/Studer (DASH) and Mitsubishi (ProDigi) in the early 1980s helped to bring about digital recording's acceptance by the major record companies.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Machines for these formats had their own transports built in as well, using reel-to-reel tape in either 1/4, 1/2, or 1-inch widths, with the audio data being recorded to the tape using a multi-track stationary tape head.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] PCM adaptors allowed for stereo digital audio recording on a conventional NTSC or PAL video tape recorder.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] The 1982 introduction of the CD by Philips and Sony popularized digital audio with consumers.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] ADAT became available in the early 1990s, which allowed eight-track 44.1 or 48 kHz recording on S-VHS cassettes, and DTRS performed a similar function with Hi8 tapes.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Like the DAT cassette, ProDigi and DASH machines also accommodated the obligatory 44.1 kHz sampling rate, but also 48 kHz on all machines, and eventually a 96 kHz sampling rate.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Unlike analog systems, modern digital audio workstations and audio interfaces allow as many channels in as many different sampling rates as the computer can effectively run at a single time.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Avid Audio and Steinberg released the first digital audio workstation software programs in 1989.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Digital audio workstations make multitrack recording and mixing much easier for large projects, which would otherwise be difficult with analog equipment.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] The rapid development and wide adoption of PCM digital telephony was enabled by metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) switched capacitor (SC) circuit technology, developed in the early 1970s.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] This led to the development of PCM codec-filter chips in the late 1970s.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] The silicon-gate CMOS (complementary MOS) PCM codec-filter chip, developed by David A.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Black in 1980, has since been the industry standard for digital telephony.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Digital audio is used in broadcasting of audio.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Standard technologies include Digital audio broadcasting (DAB), Digital Radio Mondiale (DRM), HD Radio and In-band on-channel (IBOC).
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Digital audio in recording applications is stored on audio-specific technologies including CD, DAT, Digital Compact Cassette (DCC) and MiniDisc.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Digital audio may be stored in a standard audio file formats and stored on a Hard disk recorder, Blu-ray or DVD-Audio.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Files may be played back on smartphones, computers or MP3 player.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Digital audio resolution is measured in audio bit depth.
[src:web-audio-api/digital-audio] Most digital audio formats use either 16-bit, 24-bit, and 32-bit resolution.
[src:web-audio-api/oscillatornode] The **`OscillatorNode`** interface represents a periodic waveform, such as a sine wave.
[src:web-audio-api/oscillatornode] It is an `AudioScheduledSourceNode` audio-processing module that causes a specified frequency of a given wave to be created—in effect, a constant tone.
[src:web-audio-api/oscillatornode] Creates a new instance of an `OscillatorNode` object, optionally providing an object specifying default values for the node's properties.
[src:web-audio-api/oscillatornode] As an alternative, you can use the `BaseAudioContext.createOscillator()` factory method; see Creating an AudioNode.
[src:web-audio-api/oscillatornode] An a-rate `AudioParam` representing the frequency of oscillation in hertz (though the `AudioParam` returned is read-only, the value it represents is not).
[src:web-audio-api/oscillatornode] The default value is 440 Hz (a standard middle-A note).
[src:web-audio-api/oscillatornode] An a-rate `AudioParam` representing detuning of oscillation in cents (though the `AudioParam` returned is read-only, the value it represents is not).
[src:web-audio-api/oscillatornode] A string which specifies the shape of waveform to play; this can be one of a number of standard values, or `custom` to use a `PeriodicWave` to describe a custom waveform.
[src:web-audio-api/oscillatornode] Different waves will produce different tones.
[src:web-audio-api/oscillatornode] Sets a `PeriodicWave` which describes a periodic waveform to be used instead of one of the standard waveforms; calling this sets the `type` to `custom`.
[src:web-audio-api/oscillatornode] Specifies the exact time to start playing the tone.
[src:web-audio-api/oscillatornode] Specifies the time to stop playing the tone.
[src:web-audio-api/oscillatornode] The following example shows basic usage of an `AudioContext` to create an oscillator node and to start playing a tone on it.
[src:web-audio-api/oscillatornode] For an applied example, check out our Violent Theremin demo (see app.js for relevant code).
[src:web-audio-api/oscillatornode] The four built-in oscillator types are `sine`, `square`, `triangle` and `sawtooth`.
[src:web-audio-api/oscillatornode] They are the shape of the waveform generated by an oscillator.
[src:web-audio-api/oscillatornode] Fun fact: These are the defaults for most synths because they are waveforms which are easy to generate electronically.
[src:web-audio-api/oscillatornode] This example visualizes the waveforms for the different types at different frequencies.
[src:web-audio-api/oscillatornode] The code is in two parts: in the first part, we set up the sound stuff.
[src:web-audio-api/oscillatornode] As for the second part, we draw the waveform on a canvas using the `AnalyserNode` we created above.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] A **synthesizer** (also **synthesiser** or **synth**) is an electronic musical instrument that generates audio signals.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers typically create sounds by generating waveforms through methods including subtractive synthesis, additive synthesis, and frequency modulation synthesis.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] These sounds may be altered by components such as filters, which cut or boost frequencies; envelopes, which control articulation, or how notes begin and end; and low-frequency oscillators, which modulate parameters such as pitch, volume, or filter characteristics affecting timbre.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers are typically played with keyboards or controlled by sequencers, software or other instruments, and can be synchronized to other equipment via MIDI.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Synthesizer-like instruments emerged in the United States in the mid-20th century with instruments such as the RCA Mark II, which was controlled with punch cards and used hundreds of vacuum tubes.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] The Moog synthesizer, developed by Robert Moog and first sold in 1964, is credited for pioneering concepts such as voltage-controlled oscillators, envelopes, noise generators, filters, and sequencers.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] In 1970, the smaller, cheaper Minimoog standardized synthesizers as self-contained instruments with built-in keyboards, unlike the larger modular synthesizers before it.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] In 1978, Sequential Circuits released the Prophet-5, which used microprocessors to allow users to store sounds for the first time.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] MIDI, a standardized means of synchronizing electronic instruments, was introduced in 1982 and remains an industry standard.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] The Yamaha DX7, launched in 1983, was a major success and popularized digital synthesis.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Software synthesizers now can be run as plug-ins or embedded on microchips.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] In the 21st century, analog synthesizers returned to popularity with the advent of cheaper manufacturing.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers were initially viewed as avant-garde, valued by the 1960s psychedelic and countercultural scenes but with little perceived commercial potential.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] *Switched-On Bach* (1968)*,* a bestselling album of Bach compositions arranged for synthesizer by Wendy Carlos, took synthesizers to the mainstream.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] They were adopted by electronic acts and pop and rock groups in the 1960s and 1970s and were widely used in 1980s music.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Sampling, introduced with the Fairlight synthesizer in 1979, has influenced genres such as electronic and hip hop music.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Today, the synthesizer is used in nearly every genre and is considered one of the most important instruments in the music industry.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] As electricity became more widely available, the early 20th century saw the invention of electronic musical instruments including the Telharmonium, Trautonium, ondes Martenot and theremin.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] In the late 1930s, the Hammond Organ Company built the Novachord, a large instrument powered by 72 voltage-controlled amplifiers and 146 vacuum tubes.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] In 1948, the Canadian engineer Hugh Le Caine completed the electronic sackbut, a precursor to voltage-controlled synthesizers, with keyboard sensitivity allowing for vibrato, glissando, and attack control.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] In 1957, Harry Olson and Herbert Belar completed the RCA Mark II Sound Synthesizer at the RCA laboratories in Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] The instrument read punched paper tape that controlled an analog synthesizer containing 750 vacuum tubes.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] It was acquired by the Columbia-Princeton Electronic Music Center and used almost exclusively by Milton Babbitt, a composer at Princeton University.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] The authors of *Analog Days* define "the early years of the synthesizer" as between 1964 and the mid-1970s, beginning with the debut of the Moog synthesizer, designed by the American engineer Robert Moog.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] The Moog was composed of separate modules connected by patch cables that generate, shape or control sound.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Moog developed a means of controlling pitch through voltage, the voltage-controlled oscillator.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] This, along with Moog components such as envelopes, noise generators, filters, and sequencers, became standard components in synthesizers.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Around the same period, the American engineer Don Buchla created the Buchla Modular Electronic Music System.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Instead of a conventional keyboard, Buchla's system used touchplates which transmitted control voltages depending on finger position and force.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] However, the Moog's keyboard made it more accessible and marketable to musicians, and keyboards became the standard means of controlling synthesizers.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Moog and Buchla initially avoided the word *synthesizer* for their instruments, as it was associated with the RCA synthesizer; however, by the 1970s, it had become the standard term.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] In 1970, Moog launched a cheaper, smaller synthesizer, the Minimoog.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] It was the first synthesizer sold in music stores, and was more practical for live performance.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] It standardized the concept of synthesizers as self-contained instruments with built-in keyboards.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] In the early 1970s, the British composer Ken Freeman introduced the first string synthesizer, designed to emulate string sections.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] After retail stores started selling synthesizers in 1971, other synthesizer companies were established, including ARP in the US and EMS in the UK.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] ARP's products included the ARP 2600, which folded into a carrying case and had built-in speakers, and the Odyssey, a rival to the Minimoog.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] The less expensive EMS synthesizers were used by European art rock and progressive rock acts including Brian Eno and Pink Floyd.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Designs for synthesizers appeared in the amateur electronics market, such as a design published in *Practical Electronics* in 1973.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] By the mid-1970s, ARP was the world's largest synthesizer manufacturer, though it closed in 1981.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Early synthesizers were monophonic, meaning they could only play one note at a time.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Some of the earliest commercial polyphonic synthesizers were created by the American engineer Tom Oberheim, such as the OB-X (1979).
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] In 1978, the American company Sequential Circuits released the Prophet-5, the first fully programmable polyphonic synthesizer.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Whereas previous synthesizers required users to adjust cables and knobs to change sounds, with no guarantee of exactly recreating a sound, the Prophet-5 used microprocessors to store sounds in patch memory.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] This facilitated a move from synthesizers creating unpredictable sounds to producing "a standard package of familiar sounds".
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] The synthesizer market grew dramatically in the 1980s.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] 1982 saw the introduction of MIDI, a standardized means of synchronizing electronic instruments; it remains an industry standard.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] An influential sampling synthesizer, the Fairlight CMI, was released in 1979, with the ability to record and play back samples at different pitches.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Though its high price made it inaccessible to amateurs, it was adopted by high-profile pop musicians including Kate Bush and Peter Gabriel.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] The success of the Fairlight drove competition, improving sampling technology and lowering prices.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Early competing samplers included the E-mu Emulator in 1981 and the Akai S-series in 1985.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] In 1983, Yamaha released the first commercially successful digital synthesizer, the Yamaha DX7.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Based on frequency modulation (FM) synthesis developed by the Stanford University engineer John Chowning, the DX7 was characterized by its *harsh*, *glassy* and *chilly* sounds, compared to the *warm* and *fuzzy* sounds of analog synthesis.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] The DX7 was the first synthesizer to sell more than 100,000 unitsand remains one of the bestselling in history.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Digital synthesizers typically contained preset sounds emulating acoustic instruments, with algorithms controlled with menus and buttons.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] The Synclavier, made with FM technology licensed from Yamaha, offered features such as 16-bit sampling and digital recording.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] With a starting price of $13,000, its use was limited to universities, studios and wealthy artists.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] The Roland D-50 (1987) blended Roland's linear arithmetic algorithm with samples, and was the first mass-produced synthesizer with built-in digital effects such as delay, reverb and chorus.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] In 1988, the Japanese manufacturer Korg released the M1, a digital synthesizer workstation featuring sampled transients and loops.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] With more than 250,000 units sold, it remains the bestselling synthesizer in history.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] The advent of digital synthesizers led to a downturn in interest in analog synthesizers in the following decade.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] ReBirth by Propellerhead Software and Reality by Seer Systems, the first software synthesizers that could be played in real time via MIDI, were released in 1997.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] In 1999, an update to the music software Cubase allowed users to run software instruments (including synthesizers) as plug-ins, triggering a wave of new software instruments.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Propellerhead's Reason, released in 2000, introduced an array of recognizable virtual studio equipment.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] The market for patchable and modular synthesizers rebounded in the late 1990s.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] In the 2000s, older analog synthesizers regained popularity, sometimes selling for much more than their original prices.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] In the 2010s, new, affordable analog synthesizers were introduced by companies including Moog, Korg, Arturia and Dave Smith Instruments.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] The renewed interest is credited to the appeal of imperfect *organic* sounds and simpler interfaces, and modern surface-mount technology making analog synthesizers cheaper and faster to manufacture.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Early synthesizers were viewed as avant-garde, valued by the 1960s psychedelic and counter-cultural scenes for their ability to make new sounds, but with little perceived commercial potential.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] *Switched-On Bach* (1968), a bestselling album of Bach compositions arranged for Moog synthesizer by Wendy Carlos, demonstrated that synthesizers could be more than "random noise machines", taking them to the mainstream.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] However, debates were held about the appropriateness of synthesizers in baroque music, and according to the *Guardian* they were quickly abandoned in "serious classical circles".
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Today, the synthesizer is one of the most important instruments in the music industry, used in nearly every genre.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] It is considered by the authors of *Analog Days* as "the only innovation that can stand alongside the electric guitar as a great new instrument of the age of electricity ...
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] The Moog was adopted by 1960s rock acts including the Doors, the Grateful Dead, the Rolling Stones, the Beatles, and Keith Emerson.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Emerson was the first major rock musician to perform with the Moog and it became a trademark of his performances, helping take his band Emerson, Lake & Palmer to global stardom.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] According to *Analog Days*, the likes of Emerson, with his Moog performances, "did for the keyboard what Jimi Hendrix did for the guitar".
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] String synthesizers were used by 1970s progressive rock bands including Camel, Caravan, Electric Light Orchestra, Gentle Giant and Renaissance.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] The portable Minimoog (1970), much smaller than the modular synthesizers before it, made synthesizers more common in live performance.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Early synthesizers could only play one note at a time, making them suitable for basslines, leads and solos.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] With the rise of polyphonic synthesizers in the 1970s and 1980s, "the keyboard in rock once more started to revert to the background, to be used for fills and atmosphere rather than for soloing".
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Queen included statements in their 1970s album notes specifying that no synthesisers had been used, but added them in their 1980 album *The Game*.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] The Minimoog took a place in mainstream African-American music, most notably in the work of Stevie Wonder, and in jazz, such as the work of Sun Ra.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] In the late 1970s and the early 1980s, the Minimoog was widely used in the emerging disco genre by artists including Abba and Giorgio Moroder.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Sampling, introduced with the Fairlight synthesizer in 1979, has influenced all genres of music and had a major influence on the development of electronic and hip hop music.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] In the 1970s, electronic music composers such as Jean Michel Jarre and Isao Tomita released successful synthesizer-led instrumental albums.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] This influenced the emergence of synth-pop from the late 1970s to the early 1980s.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] The sequencer-based Roland TB-303 (1981), in conjunction with the Roland TR-808 and TR-909 drum machines, became a foundation of electronic dance music genres such as house and techno when producers acquired cheap second-hand units later in the decade.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] The authors of *Analog Days* connect the synthesizer's origins in 1960s psychedelia to the raves and British Second Summer of Love of the 1980s and the club scenes of the 1990s and 2000s.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Gary Numan's 1979 hits "Are 'Friends' Electric?" and "Cars" made heavy use of synthesizers.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] OMD's "Enola Gay" (1980) used distinctive electronic percussion and a synthesized melody.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Soft Cell used a synthesized melody on their 1981 hit "Tainted Love".
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Nick Rhodes, the keyboardist of Duran Duran, used synthesizers including the Roland Jupiter-4 and Jupiter-8.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Chart hits include Depeche Mode's "Just Can't Get Enough" (1981), the Human League's "Don't You Want Me" and works by Ultravox.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] In the 1980s, digital synthesizers were widely used in pop music.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] The Yamaha DX7, released in 1983, became a pop staple, used on songs by A-ha, Kenny Loggins, Kool & the Gang.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Its E PIANO 1 preset became particularly famous, especially for power ballads, and was used by artists including Whitney Houston, Chicago, Prince, Phil Collins, Luther Vandross, Billy Ocean, and Celine Dion.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Korg M1 presets were widely used in 1990s house music, beginning with Madonna's 1990 single "Vogue".
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers are common in film and television soundtracks.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] In 1969, Mort Garson used a Moog to compose a soundtrack for the televised footage of the Apollo 11 moonwalk, creating a link between electronic music and space in the American popular imagination.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] ARP synthesizers were used to create sound effects for the 1977 science fiction films *Close Encounters of the Third Kind* and *Star Wars*, including the voice of the robot R2-D2.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] In the 1970s and 1980s, synthesizers were used in the scores for thrillers and horror films including *A Clockwork Orange* (1971), *Apocalypse Now* (1979), *The Fog* (1980) and *Manhunter* (1986).
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Brad Fiedel used a Prophet synthesizer to record the soundtrack for *The Terminator* (1984), and the filmmaker John Carpenter used them extensively for his soundtracks.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers were used to create themes for television shows including *Knight Rider* (1982)*, Twin Peaks* (1990) and *Stranger Things* (2016).
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] The rise of the synthesizer led to major changes in the music industry, including job displacement, comparable to the 1920s arrival of sound in film, which put live musicians accompanying silent films out of work.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] With its ability to imitate instruments such as strings and horns, the synthesizer threatened the jobs of session musicians by allowing one keyboardist or music programmer to produce the same range of sounds as an entire orchestra.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] For a period, the Moog was banned from use in union work, a restriction negotiated by the American Federation of Musicians (AFM).
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] The musician Walter Sear persuaded the AFM that the synthesizer demanded skill, and the category of *synthesizer player* was accepted into the union.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] However, players were subject to "suspicion and hostility" for years.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] In 1982, following a tour by Barry Manilow using synthesizers instead of an orchestra, the British Musicians' Union attempted to ban synthesizers, attracting controversy.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] In the 1980s, a few musicians skilled at programming the Yamaha DX7 found employment creating sounds for other acts.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers generate audio through various forms of analog and digital synthesis.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Oscillators produce waveforms (such as sawtooth, sine, or pulse waves) with different timbres.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Voltage-controlled amplifiers (VCAs) control the volume or gain of the audio signal.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] VCAs can be modulated by other components, such as LFOs and envelopes.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] A VCA is a preamp that boosts (amplifies) the electronic signal before passing it on to an external or built-in power amplifier, as well as a means to control its amplitude (volume) using an attenuator.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] The gain of the VCA is affected by a *control voltage* (CV), coming from an envelope generator, an LFO, the keyboard or some other source.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Envelopes control how sounds change over time.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] They may control parameters such as amplitude (volume), filters (frequencies), or pitch.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Low-frequency oscillators (LFOs) produce waveforms used to modulate parameters, such as the pitch of oscillators (producing vibrato).
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Filters remove frequencies from the audio signal, similarly to equalization, to shape sounds.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] They typically include controls to set the point at which frequencies are attenuated, and to add resonance.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Common types include low-pass filters, which remove audio above a specified frequency, and high-pass filters, which do the opposite.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Filters may be controlled with envelopes or LFOs.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Arpeggiators take input chords and convert them into arpeggios.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] They usually include controls for speed, range and mode (the movement of the arpeggio).
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers are often controlled with electronic or digital keyboards or MIDI controller keyboards, which may be built into the synthesizer unit or attached via connections such as CV/gate, USB, or MIDI.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Keyboards may offer expression such as velocity sensitivity and aftertouch, allowing for more control over the sound.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Synthesizer clones are unlicensed recreations of previous synthesizers, often marketed as affordable versions of famous musical equipment.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Clones are available as physical instruments and software.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Companies that have sold software clones include Arturia and Native Instruments.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Behringer manufactures equipment modelled on instruments including the Minimoog, Pro-One, and TB-303, and drum machines such as the TR-808.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Other synthesizer clones include the MiniMOD (a series of Eurorack modules based on the Minimoog), the Intellijel Atlantis (based on the SH-101), and the x0x Heart (based on the TB-303).
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] Creating clones of older hardware is legal where the patents have expired.
[src:web-audio-api/sound-synthesis] In 1997, Mackie lost their lawsuit against Behringer as copyright law in the United States did not cover their circuit board designs.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The Web Audio API provides a powerful and versatile system for controlling audio on the Web, allowing developers to choose audio sources, add effects to audio, create audio visualizations, apply spatial effects (such as panning) and much more.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The Web Audio API involves handling audio operations inside an **audio context**, and has been designed to allow **modular routing**.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] Basic audio operations are performed with **audio nodes**, which are linked together to form an **audio routing graph**.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] Several sources — with different types of channel layout — are supported even within a single context.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] This modular design provides the flexibility to create complex audio functions with dynamic effects.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] Audio nodes are linked into chains and simple webs by their inputs and outputs.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] They typically start with one or more sources.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] Sources provide arrays of samples — measurements of the audio signal's amplitude at successive moments in time — often tens of thousands per second.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] These could be either computed mathematically (such as `OscillatorNode`), or they can be recordings from sound/video files (like `AudioBufferSourceNode` and `MediaElementAudioSourceNode`) and audio streams (`MediaStreamAudioSourceNode`).
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] In fact, sound files are just recordings of sound intensities themselves, which come in from microphones or electric instruments, and get mixed down into a single, complicated wave.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] Outputs of these nodes could be linked to inputs of others, which mix or modify these streams of sound samples into different streams.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] A common modification is multiplying the samples by a value to make them louder or quieter (as is the case with `GainNode`).
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] Once the sound has been sufficiently processed for the intended effect, it can be linked to the input of a destination (`BaseAudioContext.destination`), which sends the sound to the speakers or headphones.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] This last connection is only necessary if the user is supposed to hear the audio.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] Connect the sources up to the effects, and the effects to the destination.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] (A simple box diagram with an outer box labeled Audio context, and three inner boxes labeled Sources, Effects and Destination.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] Timing is controlled with high precision and low latency, allowing developers to write code that responds accurately to events and is able to target specific samples, even at a high sample rate.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] So applications such as drum machines and sequencers are well within reach.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The Web Audio API also allows us to control how audio is *spatialized*.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] Using a system based on a *source-listener model*, it allows control of the *panning model* and deals with *distance-induced attenuation* induced by a moving source (or moving listener).
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The Web Audio API can seem intimidating to those that aren't familiar with audio or music terms, and as it incorporates a great deal of functionality it can prove difficult to get started if you are a developer.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] It can be used to incorporate audio into your website or application, by providing atmosphere like futurelibrary.no, or auditory feedback on forms.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] However, it can also be used to create *advanced* interactive instruments.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] With that in mind, it is suitable for both developers and musicians alike.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] We have a simple introductory tutorial for those that are familiar with programming but need a good introduction to some of the terms and structure of the API.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] There's also a Basic Concepts Behind Web Audio API article, to help you understand the way digital audio works, specifically in the realm of the API.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] This also includes a good introduction to some of the concepts the API is built upon.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] Learning coding is like playing cards — you learn the rules, then you play, then you go back and learn the rules again, then you play again.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] So if some of the theory doesn't quite fit after the first tutorial and article, there's an advanced tutorial which extends the first one to help you practice what you've learnt, and apply some more advanced techniques to build up a step sequencer.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] We also have other tutorials and comprehensive reference material available that covers all features of the API.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] If you aren't familiar with the programming basics, you might want to consult some beginner's JavaScript tutorials first and then come back here — see our Beginner's JavaScript learning module for a great place to begin.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The Web Audio API has a number of interfaces and associated events, which we have split up into nine categories of functionality.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] General containers and definitions that shape audio graphs in Web Audio API usage.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The **`AudioContext`** interface represents an audio-processing graph built from audio modules linked together, each represented by an `AudioNode`.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] An audio context controls the creation of the nodes it contains and the execution of the audio processing, or decoding.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The **`AudioNode`** interface represents an audio-processing module like an *audio source* (e.g., an HTML `<audio>` or `<video>` element), *audio destination*, *intermediate processing module* (e.g., a filter like `BiquadFilterNode`, or *volume control* like `GainNode`).
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The **`AudioParam`** interface represents an audio-related parameter, like one of an `AudioNode`.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] It can be set to a specific value or a change in value, and can be scheduled to happen at a specific time and following a specific pattern.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] Provides a map-like interface to a group of `AudioParam` interfaces, which means it provides the methods `forEach()`, `get()`, `has()`, `keys()`, and `values()`, as well as a `size` property.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The **`BaseAudioContext`** interface acts as a base definition for online and offline audio-processing graphs, as represented by `AudioContext` and `OfflineAudioContext` respectively.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] You wouldn't use `BaseAudioContext` directly — you'd use its features via one of these two inheriting interfaces.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The `ended` event is fired when playback has stopped because the end of the media was reached.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] Interfaces that define audio sources for use in the Web Audio API.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The **`AudioScheduledSourceNode`** is a parent interface for several types of audio source node interfaces.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The **`OscillatorNode`** interface represents a periodic waveform, which can be sine, square, sawtooth, triangle, or custom.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] It is an `AudioNode` audio-processing module that causes a given *frequency* of wave to be created.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The **`AudioBuffer`** interface represents a short audio asset residing in memory, created from an audio file using the `BaseAudioContext.decodeAudioData` method, or created with raw data using `BaseAudioContext.createBuffer`.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] Once decoded into this form, the audio can then be put into an `AudioBufferSourceNode`.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The **`AudioBufferSourceNode`** interface represents an audio source consisting of in-memory audio data, stored in an `AudioBuffer`.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] It is an `AudioNode` that acts as an audio source.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The **`MediaElementAudioSourceNode`** interface represents an audio source consisting of an HTML `<audio>` or `<video>` element.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The **`MediaStreamAudioSourceNode`** interface represents an audio source consisting of a `MediaStream` (such as a webcam, microphone, or a stream being sent from a remote computer).
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] If multiple audio tracks are present on the stream, the track whose `id` comes first lexicographically (alphabetically) is used.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] A node of type `MediaStreamTrackAudioSourceNode` represents an audio source whose data comes from a `MediaStreamTrack`.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] When creating the node using the `createMediaStreamTrackSource()` method to create the node, you specify which track to use.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] This provides more control than `MediaStreamAudioSourceNode`.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] Interfaces for defining effects that you want to apply to your audio sources.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The **`BiquadFilterNode`** interface represents a simple low-order filter.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] It is an `AudioNode` that can represent different kinds of filters, tone control devices, or graphic equalizers.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] A `BiquadFilterNode` always has exactly one input and one output.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The **`ConvolverNode`** interface is an `AudioNode` that performs a Linear Convolution on a given `AudioBuffer`, and is often used to achieve a reverb effect.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The **`DelayNode`** interface represents a delay-line; an `AudioNode` audio-processing module that causes a delay between the arrival of an input data and its propagation to the output.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The **`DynamicsCompressorNode`** interface provides a compression effect, which lowers the volume of the loudest parts of the signal in order to help prevent clipping and distortion that can occur when multiple sounds are played and multiplexed together at once.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The **`GainNode`** interface represents a change in volume.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] It is an `AudioNode` audio-processing module that causes a given *gain* to be applied to the input data before its propagation to the output.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The **`WaveShaperNode`** interface represents a non-linear distorter.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] It is an `AudioNode` that use a curve to apply a waveshaping distortion to the signal.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] Beside obvious distortion effects, it is often used to add a warm feeling to the signal.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] Describes a periodic waveform that can be used to shape the output of an `OscillatorNode`.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] Implements a general infinite impulse response (IIR) filter; this type of filter can be used to implement tone-control devices and graphic equalizers as well.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] Once you are done processing your audio, these interfaces define where to output it.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The **`AudioDestinationNode`** interface represents the end destination of an audio source in a given context — usually the speakers of your device.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The **`MediaStreamAudioDestinationNode`** interface represents an audio destination consisting of a WebRTC `MediaStream` with a single `AudioMediaStreamTrack`, which can be used in a similar way to a `MediaStream` obtained from `getUserMedia()`.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] It is an `AudioNode` that acts as an audio destination.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] Interfaces for extracting audio graph statistics, for the purposes of data analysis and visualization.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] Represents a node able to provide real-time frequency and time-domain analysis information.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] Provides access to duration, underrun, and latency statistics for the associated `AudioContext`.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] These statistics allow you to measure audio delay and glitches.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] To split and merge audio channels, you'll use these interfaces.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The **`ChannelSplitterNode`** interface separates the different channels of an audio source out into a set of *mono* outputs.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The **`ChannelMergerNode`** interface reunites different mono inputs into a single output.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] Each input will be used to fill a channel of the output.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] These interfaces allow you to add audio spatialization panning effects to your audio sources.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The **`AudioListener`** interface represents the position and orientation of the unique person listening to the audio scene used in audio spatialization.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The **`PannerNode`** interface represents the position and behavior of an audio source signal in 3D space, allowing you to create complex panning effects.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The **`StereoPannerNode`** interface represents a simple stereo panner node that can be used to pan an audio stream left or right.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] Using audio worklets, you can define custom audio nodes written in JavaScript or WebAssembly.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] Audio worklets implement the `Worklet` interface, a lightweight version of the `Worker` interface.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The `AudioWorklet` interface is available through the `AudioContext` object's `audioWorklet`, and lets you add modules to the audio worklet to be executed off the main thread.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The `AudioWorkletNode` interface represents an `AudioNode` that is embedded into an audio graph and can pass messages to the corresponding `AudioWorkletProcessor`.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The `AudioWorkletProcessor` interface represents audio processing code running in an `AudioWorkletGlobalScope` that generates, processes, or analyzes audio directly, and can pass messages to the corresponding `AudioWorkletNode`.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] Before audio worklets were defined, the Web Audio API used the `ScriptProcessorNode` for JavaScript-based audio processing.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] Because the code runs in the main thread, they have bad performance.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The `ScriptProcessorNode` is kept for historic reasons but is marked as deprecated.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The **`ScriptProcessorNode`** interface allows the generation, processing, or analyzing of audio using JavaScript.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] It is an `AudioNode` audio-processing module that is linked to two buffers, one containing the current input, one containing the output.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] An event, implementing the `AudioProcessingEvent` interface, is sent to the object each time the input buffer contains new data, and the event handler terminates when it has filled the output buffer with data.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The `audioprocess` event is fired when an input buffer of a Web Audio API `ScriptProcessorNode` is ready to be processed.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The `AudioProcessingEvent` represents events that occur when a `ScriptProcessorNode` input buffer is ready to be processed.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] It is possible to process/render an audio graph very quickly in the background — rendering it to an `AudioBuffer` rather than to the device's speakers — with the following.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The **`OfflineAudioContext`** interface is an `AudioContext` interface representing an audio-processing graph built from linked together `AudioNode`s.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] In contrast with a standard `AudioContext`, an `OfflineAudioContext` doesn't really render the audio but rather generates it, *as fast as it can*, in a buffer.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The `complete` event is fired when the rendering of an `OfflineAudioContext` is terminated.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The `OfflineAudioCompletionEvent` represents events that occur when the processing of an `OfflineAudioContext` is terminated.
[src:web-audio-api/web-audio-api] The `complete` event uses this interface.
